# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: prim-mst
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] It was first published in 1926 by Otakar Borůvka as a method of constructing an efficient electricity network for Moravia.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] The algorithm was rediscovered by Choquet in 1938; again by Florek, Łukasiewicz, Perkal, Steinhaus, and Zubrzycki in 1951; and again by Georges Sollin in 1965.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] This algorithm is frequently called **Sollin's algorithm**, especially in the parallel computing literature.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] The algorithm begins by finding the minimum-weight edge incident to each vertex of the graph, and adding all of those edges to the forest.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] Then, it repeats a similar process of finding the minimum-weight edge from each tree constructed so far to a different tree, and adding all of those edges to the forest.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] Each repetition of this process reduces the number of trees, within each connected component of the graph, to at most half of this former value, so after logarithmically many repetitions the process finishes.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] When it does, the set of edges it has added forms the minimum spanning forest.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] The following pseudocode illustrates a basic implementation of Borůvka's algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] In the conditional clauses, every edge *uv* is considered cheaper than "None".
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] The purpose of the *completed* variable is to determine whether the forest *F* is yet a spanning forest.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] If edges do not have distinct weights, then a consistent **tie-breaking rule** must be used, e.g. based on some total order on vertices or edges.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] This can be achieved by representing vertices as integers and comparing them directly; comparing their memory addresses; etc.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] A tie-breaking rule is necessary to ensure that the created graph is indeed a forest, that is, it does not contain cycles.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] For example, consider a triangle graph with nodes {*a*,*b*,*c*} and all edges of weight 1.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] Then a cycle could be created if we select *ab* as the minimal weight edge for {*a*}, *bc* for {*b*}, and *ca* for {*c*}.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] A tie-breaking rule which orders edges first by source, then by destination, will prevent creation of a cycle, resulting in the minimal spanning tree {*ab*, *bc*}.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] As an optimization, one could remove from *G* each edge that is found to connect two vertices in the same component, so that it does not contribute to the time for searching for cheapest edges in later components.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] Borůvka's algorithm can be shown to take O(log *V*) iterations of the outer loop until it terminates, and therefore to run in time O(*E* log *V*), where E is the number of edges, and V is the number of vertices in G (assuming *E* ≥ *V*).
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] In planar graphs, and more generally in families of graphs closed under graph minor operations, it can be made to run in linear time, by removing all but the cheapest edge between each pair of components after each stage of the algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] Other algorithms for this problem include Prim's algorithm and Kruskal's algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] Fast parallel algorithms can be obtained by combining Prim's algorithm with Borůvka's.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] A faster randomized minimum spanning tree algorithm based in part on Borůvka's algorithm due to Karger, Klein, and Tarjan runs in expected O(*E*) time.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] The best known (deterministic) minimum spanning tree algorithm by Bernard Chazelle is also based in part on Borůvka's and runs in O(*E* α(*E*,*V*)) time, where α is the inverse Ackermann function.
[src:prim-mst/borůvka-s-algorithm] These randomized and deterministic algorithms combine steps of Borůvka's algorithm, reducing the number of components that remain to be connected, with steps of a different type that reduce the number of edges between pairs of components.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] In graph theory, a **cut** is a partition of the vertices of a graph into two disjoint subsets.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] Any cut determines a **cut-set**, the set of edges that have one endpoint in each subset of the partition.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] These edges are said to **cross** the cut.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] In a connected graph, each cut-set determines a unique cut, and in some cases cuts are identified with their cut-sets rather than with their vertex partitions.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] In a flow network, an **s–t cut** is a cut that requires the *source* and the *sink* to be in different subsets, and its *cut-set* only consists of edges going from the source's side to the sink's side.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] The *capacity* of an s–t cut is defined as the sum of the capacity of each edge in the *cut-set*.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] A **cut** *C* = (*S*, *T*) is a partition of V of a graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) into two subsets S and T.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] The **cut-set** of a cut *C* = (*S*, *T*) is the set {(*u*, *v*) ∈ *E* | *u* ∈ *S*, *v* ∈ *T*} of edges that have one endpoint in S and the other endpoint in T.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] If s and t are specified vertices of the graph G, then an **s–t cut** is a cut in which s belongs to the set S and t belongs to the set T.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] In an unweighted undirected graph, the *size* or *weight* of a cut is the number of edges crossing the cut.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] In a weighted graph, the **value** or **weight** is defined by the sum of the weights of the edges crossing the cut.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] A **bond** is a cut-set that does not have any other cut-set as a proper subset.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] A cut is *minimum* if the size or weight of the cut is not larger than the size of any other cut.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] The illustration on the right shows a minimum cut: the size of this cut is 2, and there is no cut of size 1 because the graph is bridgeless.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] The max-flow min-cut theorem proves that the maximum network flow and the sum of the cut-edge weights of any minimum cut that separates the source and the sink are equal.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] There are polynomial-time methods to solve the min-cut problem, notably the Edmonds–Karp algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] A cut is *maximum* if the size of the cut is not smaller than the size of any other cut.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] The illustration on the right shows a maximum cut: the size of the cut is equal to 5, and there is no cut of size 6, or |*E*| (the number of edges), because the graph is not bipartite (there is an odd cycle).
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] In general, finding a maximum cut is computationally hard.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] The max-cut problem is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] The max-cut problem is also APX-hard, meaning that there is no polynomial-time approximation scheme for it unless P = NP.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] However, it can be approximated to within a constant approximation ratio using semidefinite programming.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] Note that min-cut and max-cut are *not* dual problems in the linear programming sense, even though one gets from one problem to other by changing min to max in the objective function.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] The max-flow problem is the dual of the min-cut problem.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] The **sparsest cut problem** is to bipartition the vertices so as to minimize the ratio of the number of edges across the cut divided by the number of vertices in the smaller half of the partition.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] This objective function favors solutions that are both sparse (few edges crossing the cut) and balanced (close to a bisection).
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] The problem is known to be NP-hard, and the best known approximation algorithm is an $O({\sqrt {\log n}})$ approximation due to Arora, Rao & Vazirani (2009).
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] The family of all cut sets of an undirected graph is known as the **cut space** of the graph.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] It forms a vector space over the two-element finite field of arithmetic modulo two, with the symmetric difference of two cut sets as the vector addition operation, and is the orthogonal complement of the cycle space.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] If the edges of the graph are given positive weights, the minimum weight basis of the cut space can be described by a tree on the same vertex set as the graph, called the Gomory–Hu tree.
[src:prim-mst/cut-graph-theory] Each edge of this tree is associated with a bond in the original graph, and the minimum cut between two nodes *s* and *t* is the minimum weight bond among the ones associated with the path from *s* to *t* in the tree.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] A **greedy algorithm** is an algorithm which, at each step, makes the choice that is locally optimal, and subsequently does not reconsider past choices.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Greedy algorithms are often used to solve combinatorial optimization problems.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] If an optimization problem only depends on the partial solution of solving it for one subproblem, we can solve this problem by "greedily" considering only the locally optimal subproblem.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] In this sense, a greedy algorithm is a special case of a dynamic programming algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] In many cases, a greedy algorithm does not produce an exact solution, but can yield solutions that approximate an exact solution in a reasonable amount of time.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] An example of a problem which admits an exact greedy solution, the activity selection problem.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Given a collection of tasks which can be done between allotted time intervals, the problem is to determine the maximum number of tasks that can be done.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] A greedy algorithm in $O(n\log(n))$ which solves this problem sorts the tasks by the end time and then repeatedly chooses the first task that begins after the last task ended.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Many classic algorithms in computer science such as the Huffman coding algorithm, Prim's algorithm, Kruskal's algorithm, and Dijkstra's algorithm all use greedy properties in their design.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Mathematicians frequently use *greedy strategies* in proofs as well.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] A classic example is what Raphael Yuster refers to as the greedy proof that every tournament in graph contains a Hamiltonian path.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Since there is no formal definition of what a greedy algorithm is, a complete characterization of when a problem admits a greedy algorithm as a solution is not known.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] However, special cases have been identified.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Jack Edmonds showed that a greedy algorithm can be used to solve a class of linear combinatorial optimization problems with a matroid structure.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Later Bernhard Korte and László Lovász characterized a broader class of optimization problems by introducing the notion of a greedoid.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] This allowed, for example, a proof of the optimality of Prim's algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Algorithms which undo past steps are not greedy.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] For example, the Gale-Shapley algorithm is not a greedy algorithm since although it constructs a solution by choosing the current best pairing, in the process, existing solutions may be modified.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] One technique used to prove the optimiality of greedy algorithms is an exchange argument.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] The exchange argument demonstrates that any solution different from the greedy solution is at most as good as the greedy solution.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Conclude by induction that the greedy solution is optimal.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Starting from A, a greedy algorithm that tries to find the maximum by following the greatest slope will find the local maximum at "m", oblivious to the global maximum at "M".
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] To reach the largest sum, at each step, the greedy algorithm will choose what appears to be the optimal immediate choice, so it will choose 12 instead of 3 at the second step, and will not reach the best solution, which contains 99.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Graph theory is a rich source of greedy algorithms.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Computing scientists frequently use greedy algorithms frequently to compute graph invariants.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Greedy algorithms are also used to find upper bounds for the chromatic numbers.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] A simple example is the bound $\chi (G)\leq \Delta (G)+1$ obtained by a greedy algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] We begin by taking a vertex that has not been colored.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Since it has at most $\Delta (G)$ neighbours, at most $\Delta (G)$ colors are used in adjacent vertices, leaving a color free for the vertex under consideration.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] A solution to the NP-complete travelling salesman problem can be approximated by starting from an empty edge set and then adding the next cheapest edge which is a subgraph of a complete tour.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] This greedy algorithm has been proven to yield at most $\Theta (\log n)$ times longer than the optimal tour.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Another example is that a solution for the 0-1 knapsack problem can be approximated by using the greedy algorithm for the fractional knapsack problem.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] This greedy algorithm has been proven to yield a solution at least half the value of the optimal solution.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Solutions for submodular maximization are approximated using a greedy algorithm which yields a solution at least half the value of the optimal solution.
[src:prim-mst/greedy-algorithm] Problems for which greedy algorithms are used to provide approximation algorithms include the set cover, load balancing, Steiner tree and independent set problem.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A **minimum spanning tree** (**MST**) or **minimum weight spanning tree** is a subset of the edges of a connected, edge-weighted undirected graph that connects all the vertices together, without any cycles and with the minimum possible total edge weight.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] That is, it is a spanning tree whose sum of edge weights is as small as possible.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] More generally, any edge-weighted undirected graph (not necessarily connected) has a **minimum spanning forest**, which is a union of the minimum spanning trees for its connected components.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] There are many use cases for minimum spanning trees.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] One example is a telecommunications company trying to lay cable in a new neighborhood.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If it is constrained to bury the cable only along certain paths (e.g. roads), then there would be a graph containing the points (e.g. houses) connected by those paths.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Some of the paths might be more expensive, because they are longer, or require the cable to be buried deeper; these paths would be represented by edges with larger weights.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Currency is an acceptable unit for edge weight – there is no requirement for edge lengths to obey normal rules of geometry such as the triangle inequality.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A *spanning tree* for that graph would be a subset of those paths that has no cycles but still connects every house; there might be several spanning trees possible.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A *minimum spanning tree* would be one with the lowest total cost, representing the least expensive path for laying the cable.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If there are n vertices in the graph, then each spanning tree has *n* − 1 edges.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] There may be several minimum spanning trees of the same weight; in particular, if all the edge weights of a given graph are the same, then every spanning tree of that graph is minimum.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Since A and B differ despite containing the same nodes, there is at least one edge that belongs to one but not the other.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Among such edges, let *e*1 be the one with least weight; this choice is unique because the edge weights are all distinct.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Without loss of generality, assume *e*1 is in A.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] As B is an MST, {*e*1} ∪ *B* must contain a cycle C with *e*1.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] As a tree, A contains no cycles, therefore C must have an edge *e*2 that is not in A.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Since *e*1 was chosen as the unique lowest-weight edge among those belonging to exactly one of A and B, the weight of *e*2 must be greater than the weight of *e*1.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] As *e*1 and *e*2 are part of the cycle C, replacing *e*2 with *e*1 in B therefore yields a spanning tree with a smaller weight.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] This contradicts the assumption that B is an MST.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] More generally, if the edge weights are not all distinct then only the (multi-)set of weights in minimum spanning trees is certain to be unique; it is the same for all minimum spanning trees.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If the weights are *positive*, then a minimum spanning tree is, in fact, a minimum-cost subgraph connecting all vertices, since if a subgraph contains a cycle, removing any edge along that cycle will decrease its cost and preserve connectivity.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: Assume the contrary, i.e. that e belongs to an MST *T*1.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Then deleting e will break *T*1 into two subtrees with the two ends of e in different subtrees.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The remainder of C reconnects the subtrees, hence there is an edge f of C with ends in different subtrees, i.e., it reconnects the subtrees into a tree *T*2 with weight less than that of *T*1, because the weight of f is less than the weight of e.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: Assume that there is an MST T that does not contain e.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Adding e to T will produce a cycle, that crosses the cut once at e and crosses back at another edge e'.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Deleting e' we get a spanning tree *T*∖{*e'*} ∪ {*e*} of strictly smaller weight than T.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] This contradicts the assumption that T was a MST.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] By a similar argument, if more than one edge is of minimum weight across a cut, then each such edge is contained in some minimum spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Proof: if e was not included in the MST, removing any of the (larger cost) edges in the cycle formed after adding e to the MST, would yield a spanning tree of smaller weight.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If T is a tree of MST edges, then we can *contract* T into a single vertex while maintaining the invariant that the MST of the contracted graph plus T gives the MST for the graph before contraction.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] In all of the algorithms below, m is the number of edges in the graph and n is the number of vertices.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The first algorithm for finding a minimum spanning tree was developed by Czech scientist Otakar Borůvka in 1926 (see Borůvka's algorithm).
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Its purpose was an efficient electrical coverage of Moravia.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The algorithm proceeds in a sequence of stages.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] In each stage, called *Boruvka step*, it identifies a forest F consisting of the minimum-weight edge incident to each vertex in the graph G, then forms the graph *G*1 = *G* \ *F* as the input to the next step.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Here *G* \ *F* denotes the graph derived from G by contracting edges in F (by the Cut property, these edges belong to the MST).
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Since the number of vertices is reduced by at least half in each step, Boruvka's algorithm takes *O*(*m* log *n*) time.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A second algorithm is Prim's algorithm, which was invented by Vojtěch Jarník in 1930 and rediscovered by Prim in 1957 and Dijkstra in 1959.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Basically, it grows the MST (T) one edge at a time.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Initially, T contains an arbitrary vertex.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] In each step, T is augmented with a least-weight edge (*x*,*y*) such that x is in T and y is not yet in T.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] By the Cut property, all edges added to T are in the MST.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Its run-time is either *O*(*m* log *n*) or *O*(*m* + *n* log *n*), depending on the data-structures used.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A third algorithm commonly in use is Kruskal's algorithm, which also takes *O*(*m* log *n*) time.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A fourth algorithm, not as commonly used, is the reverse-delete algorithm, which is the reverse of Kruskal's algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Its runtime is O(*m* log *n* (log log *n*)3).
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] All four of these are greedy algorithms.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Since they run in polynomial time, the problem of finding such trees is in **FP**, and related decision problems such as determining whether a particular edge is in the MST or determining if the minimum total weight exceeds a certain value are in **P**.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Several researchers have tried to find more computationally-efficient algorithms.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] In a comparison model, in which the only allowed operations on edge weights are pairwise comparisons, Karger, Klein & Tarjan (1995) found a linear time randomized algorithm based on a combination of Borůvka's algorithm and the reverse-delete algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The fastest non-randomized comparison-based algorithm with known complexity, by Bernard Chazelle, is based on the soft heap, an approximate priority queue.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Its running time is *O*(*m* α(*m*,*n*)), where α is the classical functional inverse of the Ackermann function.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The function α grows extremely slowly, so that for all practical purposes it may be considered a constant no greater than 4; thus Chazelle's algorithm takes very close to linear time.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] *m*/*n* ≥ log log log *n*), then a deterministic algorithm by Fredman and Tarjan finds the MST in time O(*m*).
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The algorithm executes a number of phases.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Each phase executes Prim's algorithm many times, each for a limited number of steps.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The run-time of each phase is O(*m* + *n*).
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If the number of vertices before a phase is n', the number of vertices remaining after a phase is at most ${\tfrac {n'}{2^{m/n'}}}$ .
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Hence, at most log**n* phases are needed, which gives a linear run-time for dense graphs.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] There are other algorithms that work in linear time on dense graphs.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If the edge weights are integers represented in binary, then deterministic algorithms are known that solve the problem in *O*(*m* + *n*) integer operations.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Whether the problem can be solved *deterministically* for a *general graph* in *linear time* by a comparison-based algorithm remains an open question.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Deterministic algorithms are known that solve the problem for planar graphs in linear time.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] By the Euler characteristic of planar graphs, *m* ≤ 3*n* - 6 ∈ *O*(*n*), so this is in time *O*(*n*).
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Given graph G where the nodes and edges are fixed but the weights are unknown, it is possible to construct a binary decision tree (DT) for calculating the MST for any permutation of weights.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Each internal node of the DT contains a comparison between two edges, e.g.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] "Is the weight of the edge between x and y larger than the weight of the edge between w and z?".
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The two children of the node correspond to the two possible answers "yes" or "no".
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] In each leaf of the DT, there is a list of edges from G that correspond to an MST.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime complexity of a DT is the largest number of queries required to find the MST, which is just the depth of the DT.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A DT for a graph G is called *optimal* if it has the smallest depth of all correct DTs for G.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] For every integer r, it is possible to find optimal decision trees for all graphs on r vertices by brute-force search.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Seth Pettie and Vijaya Ramachandran have found a provably optimal deterministic comparison-based minimum spanning tree algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The following is a simplified description of the algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Partition the graph to components with at most r vertices in each component.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] This partition uses a soft heap, which "corrupts" a small number of the edges of the graph.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Use the optimal decision trees to find an MST for the uncorrupted subgraph within each component.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Add back the corrupted edges to the resulting forest to form a subgraph guaranteed to contain the minimum spanning tree, and smaller by a constant factor than the starting graph.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Apply the optimal algorithm recursively to this graph.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime of all steps in the algorithm is *O*(*m*), *except for the step of using the decision trees*.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The runtime of this step is unknown, but it has been proved that it is optimal - no algorithm can do better than the optimal decision tree.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Thus, this algorithm has the peculiar property that it is *provably optimal* although its runtime complexity is *unknown*.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Research has also considered parallel algorithms for the minimum spanning tree problem.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] With a linear number of processors it is possible to solve the problem in *O*(log *n*) time.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The problem can also be approached in a distributed manner.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If each node is considered a computer and no node knows anything except its own connected links, one can still calculate the distributed minimum spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Frieze and Steele also proved convergence in probability.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Svante Janson proved a central limit theorem for weight of the MST.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] For uniform random weights in $[0,1]$ , the exact expected size of the minimum spanning tree has been computed for small complete graphs.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] There is a fractional variant of the MST, in which each edge is allowed to appear "fractionally".
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Formally, a **fractional spanning set** of a graph (V,E) is a nonnegative function *f* on *E* such that, for every non-trivial subset *W* of *V* (i.e., *W* is neither empty nor equal to *V*), the sum of *f*(*e*) over all edges connecting a node of *W* with a node of *V*\*W* is at least 1.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Intuitively, *f*(*e*) represents the fraction of e that is contained in the spanning set.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] A **minimum fractional spanning set** is a fractional spanning set for which the sum $\sum _{e\in E}f(e)\cdot w(e)$ is as small as possible.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] If the fractions *f*(*e*) are forced to be in {0,1}, then the set *T* of edges with f(e)=1 are a spanning set, as every node or subset of nodes is connected to the rest of the graph by at least one edge of *T*.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Moreover, if *f* minimizes $\sum _{e\in E}f(e)\cdot w(e)$ , then the resulting spanning set is necessarily a tree, since if it contained a cycle, then an edge could be removed without affecting the spanning condition.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] The fractional MST problem can be solved in polynomial time using the ellipsoid method.
[src:prim-mst/minimum-spanning-tree] Minimum spanning trees have direct applications in the design of networks, including computer networks, telecommunications networks, transportation networks, water supply networks, and electrical grids (which they were first invented for, as mentioned above).
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] In computer science, **Prim's algorithm** is a greedy algorithm that finds a minimum spanning tree for a weighted undirected graph.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] This means it finds a subset of the edges that forms a tree that includes every vertex, where the total weight of all the edges in the tree is minimized.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] The algorithm operates by building this tree one vertex at a time, from an arbitrary starting vertex, at each step adding the cheapest possible connection from the tree to another vertex.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] The algorithm was developed in 1930 by Czech mathematician Vojtěch Jarník and later rediscovered and republished by computer scientists Robert C.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Therefore, it is also sometimes called **Jarník's algorithm**, the **Prim–Jarník algorithm**, the **Prim–Dijkstra algorithm** or the **DJP algorithm**.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Other well-known algorithms for this problem include Kruskal's algorithm and Borůvka's algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] These algorithms find the minimum spanning forest in a possibly disconnected graph; in contrast, the most basic form of Prim's algorithm only finds minimum spanning trees in connected graphs.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] However, running Prim's algorithm separately for each connected component of the graph, it can also be used to find the minimum spanning forest.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] In terms of their asymptotic time complexity, these three algorithms are equally fast for sparse graphs, but slower than other more sophisticated algorithms.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] However, for graphs that are sufficiently dense, Prim's algorithm can be made to run in linear time, meeting or improving the time bounds for other algorithms.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Grow the tree by one edge: Of the edges that connect the tree to vertices not yet in the tree, find the minimum-weight edge, and transfer it to the tree.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Repeat step 2 (until all vertices are in the tree).
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] In more detail, it may be implemented following the pseudocode below.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Different variations of the algorithm differ from each other in how the set *Q* is implemented: as a simple linked list or array of vertices, or as a more complicated priority queue data structure.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] This choice leads to differences in the time complexity of the algorithm.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] In general, a priority queue will be quicker at finding the vertex *v* with minimum cost, but will entail more expensive updates when the value of *C*[*w*] changes.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] The time complexity of Prim's algorithm depends on the data structures used for the graph and for ordering the edges by weight, which can be done using a priority queue.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] A simple implementation of Prim's, using an adjacency matrix or an adjacency list graph representation and linearly searching an array of weights to find the minimum weight edge to add, requires O(|V|2) running time.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] However, this running time can be greatly improved by using heaps to implement finding minimum weight edges in the algorithm's inner loop.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] A first improved version uses a heap to store all edges of the input graph, ordered by their weight.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] This leads to an O(|E| log |E|) worst-case running time.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] But storing vertices instead of edges can improve it still further.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] The heap should order the vertices by the smallest edge-weight that connects them to any vertex in the partially constructed minimum spanning tree (MST) (or infinity if no such edge exists).
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Every time a vertex *v* is chosen and added to the MST, a decrease-key operation is performed on all vertices *w* outside the partial MST such that *v* is connected to *w*, setting the key to the minimum of its previous value and the edge cost of (*v*,*w*).
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Using a simple binary heap data structure, Prim's algorithm can now be shown to run in time O(|E| log |V|) where |E| is the number of edges and |V| is the number of vertices.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Using a more sophisticated Fibonacci heap, this can be brought down to O(|E| + |V| log |V|), which is asymptotically faster when the graph is dense enough that |E| is ω(|V|), and linear time when |E| is at least |V| log |V|.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] For graphs of even greater density (having at least |V|*c* edges for some *c* > 1), Prim's algorithm can be made to run in linear time even more simply, by using a *d*-ary heap in place of a Fibonacci heap.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] At every iteration of Prim's algorithm, an edge must be found that connects a vertex in a subgraph to a vertex outside the subgraph.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Since *P* is connected, there will always be a path to every vertex.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] The output *Y* of Prim's algorithm is a tree, because the edge and vertex added to tree *Y* are connected.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Let *Y1* be a minimum spanning tree of graph P.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] If *Y1*=*Y* then *Y* is a minimum spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Otherwise, let *e* be the first edge added during the construction of tree *Y* that is not in tree *Y1*, and *V* be the set of vertices connected by the edges added before edge *e*.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Then one endpoint of edge *e* is in set *V* and the other is not.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Since tree *Y1* is a spanning tree of graph *P*, there is a path in tree *Y1* joining the two endpoints.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] As one travels along the path, one must encounter an edge *f* joining a vertex in set *V* to one that is not in set *V*.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Let tree *Y2* be the graph obtained by removing edge *f* from and adding edge *e* to tree *Y1*.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Repeat the steps above and we will eventually obtain a minimum spanning tree of graph *P* that is identical to tree *Y*.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] This shows *Y* is a minimum spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] The minimum spanning tree allows for the first subset of the sub-region to be expanded into a larger subset *X*, which we assume to be the minimum.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] The main loop of Prim's algorithm is inherently sequential and thus not parallelizable.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] However, the inner loop, which determines the next edge of minimum weight that does not form a cycle, can be parallelized by dividing the vertices and edges between the available processors.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] The following pseudocode demonstrates this.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Create C, E, F, and Q as in the sequential algorithm and divide C, E, as well as the graph between all processors such that each processor holds the incoming edges to its set of vertices.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] Let $C_{i}$ , $E_{i}$ denote the parts of *C*, *E* stored on processor $P_{i}$ .
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] This algorithm can generally be implemented on distributed machines as well as on shared memory machines.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] The running time is $O({\tfrac {|V|^{2}}{|P|}})+O(|V|\log |P|)$ , assuming that the *reduce* and *broadcast* operations can be performed in $O(\log |P|)$ .
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] A variant of Prim's algorithm for shared memory machines, in which Prim's sequential algorithm is being run in parallel, starting from different vertices, has also been explored.
[src:prim-mst/prim-s-algorithm] It should, however, be noted that more sophisticated algorithms exist to solve the distributed minimum spanning tree problem in a more efficient manner.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] In the mathematical field of graph theory, a **spanning tree** *T* of an undirected graph *G* is a subgraph that is a tree which includes all of the vertices of *G*.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] In general, a graph may have several spanning trees, but a graph that is not connected will not contain a spanning tree (see about spanning forests below).
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] If all of the edges of *G* are also edges of a spanning tree *T* of *G*, then *G* is a tree and is identical to *T* (that is, a tree has a unique spanning tree and it is itself).
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Several pathfinding algorithms, including Dijkstra's algorithm and the A* search algorithm, internally build a spanning tree as an intermediate step in solving the problem.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] In order to minimize the cost of power networks, wiring connections, piping, automatic speech recognition, etc., people often use algorithms that gradually build a spanning tree (or many such trees) as intermediate steps in the process of finding the minimum spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] The Internet and many other telecommunications networks have transmission links that connect nodes together in a mesh topology that includes some loops.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] In order to avoid bridge loops and routing loops, many routing protocols designed for such networks—including the Spanning Tree Protocol, Open Shortest Path First, Link-state routing protocol, Augmented tree-based routing, etc.—require each router to remember a spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] A special kind of spanning tree, the Xuong tree, is used in topological graph theory to find graph embeddings with maximum genus.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] A Xuong tree is a spanning tree such that, in the remaining graph, the number of connected components with an odd number of edges is as small as possible.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] A Xuong tree and an associated maximum-genus embedding can be found in polynomial time.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] A tree is a connected undirected graph with no cycles.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] It is a spanning tree of a graph *G* if it spans *G* (that is, it includes every vertex of *G*) and is a subgraph of *G* (every edge in the tree belongs to *G*).
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] A spanning tree of a connected graph *G* can also be defined as a maximal set of edges of *G* that contains no cycle, or as a minimal set of edges that connect all vertices.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Adding just one edge to a spanning tree will create a cycle; such a cycle is called a **fundamental cycle** with respect to that tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] There is a distinct fundamental cycle for each edge not in the spanning tree; thus, there is a one-to-one correspondence between fundamental cycles and edges not in the spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] For any given spanning tree the set of all *E* − *V* + 1 fundamental cycles forms a cycle basis, i.e., a basis for the cycle space.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Dual to the notion of a fundamental cycle is the notion of a **fundamental cutset** with respect to a given spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] By deleting just one edge of the spanning tree, the vertices are partitioned into two disjoint sets.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] The fundamental cutset is defined as the set of edges that must be removed from the graph *G* to accomplish the same partition.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Thus, each spanning tree defines a set of *V* − 1 fundamental cutsets, one for each edge of the spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] A collection of disjoint (unconnected) trees is described as a *forest*.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] A *spanning forest* in a graph is a subgraph that is a forest with an additional requirement.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] There are two incompatible requirements in use, of which one is relatively rare.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] The number *t*(*G*) of spanning trees of a connected graph is a well-studied invariant.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] More generally, for any graph *G*, the number *t*(*G*) can be calculated in polynomial time as the determinant of a matrix derived from the graph, using Kirchhoff's matrix-tree theorem.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Specifically, to compute *t*(*G*), one constructs the Laplacian matrix of the graph, a square matrix in which the rows and columns are both indexed by the vertices of *G*.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] The resulting matrix is singular, so its determinant is zero.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] However, deleting the row and column for an arbitrarily chosen vertex leads to a smaller matrix whose determinant is exactly *t*(*G*).
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] The term *t*(*G* − *e*) in this formula counts the spanning trees of *G* that do not use edge *e*, and the term *t*(*G*/*e*) counts the spanning trees of *G* that use *e*.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] In this formula, if the given graph *G* is a multigraph, or if a contraction causes two vertices to be connected to each other by multiple edges, then the redundant edges should not be removed, as that would lead to the wrong total.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] For instance a bond graph connecting two vertices by *k* edges has *k* different spanning trees, each consisting of a single one of these edges.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] The Tutte polynomial of a graph can be defined as a sum, over the spanning trees of the graph, of terms computed from the "internal activity" and "external activity" of the tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Its value at the arguments (1,1) is the number of spanning trees or, in a disconnected graph, the number of maximal spanning forests.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] The Tutte polynomial can also be computed using a deletion-contraction recurrence, but its computational complexity is high: for many values of its arguments, computing it exactly is #P-complete, and it is also hard to approximate with a guaranteed approximation ratio.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] The point (1,1), at which it can be evaluated using Kirchhoff's theorem, is one of the few exceptions.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] A single spanning tree of a graph can be found in linear time by either depth-first search or breadth-first search.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Both of these algorithms explore the given graph, starting from an arbitrary vertex *v*, by looping through the neighbors of the vertices they discover and adding each unexplored neighbor to a data structure to be explored later.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] They differ in whether this data structure is a stack (in the case of depth-first search) or a queue (in the case of breadth-first search).
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] In either case, one can form a spanning tree by connecting each vertex, other than the root vertex *v*, to the vertex from which it was discovered.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] This tree is known as a depth-first search tree or a breadth-first search tree according to the graph exploration algorithm used to construct it.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Depth-first search trees are a special case of a class of spanning trees called Trémaux trees, named after the 19th-century discoverer of depth-first search.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Spanning trees are important in parallel and distributed computing, as a way of maintaining communications between a set of processors; see for instance the Spanning Tree Protocol used by OSI link layer devices or the Shout (protocol) for distributed computing.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] However, the depth-first and breadth-first methods for constructing spanning trees on sequential computers are not well suited for parallel and distributed computers.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Instead, researchers have devised several more specialized algorithms for finding spanning trees in these models of computation.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] In certain fields of graph theory it is often useful to find a minimum spanning tree of a weighted graph.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Optimal spanning tree problems have also been studied for finite sets of points in a geometric space such as the Euclidean plane.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] For such an input, a spanning tree is again a tree that has as its vertices the given points.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] The quality of the tree is measured in the same way as in a graph, using the Euclidean distance between pairs of points as the weight for each edge.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Thus, for instance, a Euclidean minimum spanning tree is the same as a graph minimum spanning tree in a complete graph with Euclidean edge weights.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] A spanning tree chosen randomly from among all the spanning trees with equal probability is called a uniform spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Wilson's algorithm can be used to generate uniform spanning trees in polynomial time by a process of taking a random walk on the given graph and erasing the cycles created by this walk.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] An alternative model for generating spanning trees randomly but not uniformly is the random minimal spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] In this model, the edges of the graph are assigned random weights and then the minimum spanning tree of the weighted graph is constructed.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Because a graph may have exponentially many spanning trees, it is not possible to list them all in polynomial time.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] However, algorithms are known for listing all spanning trees in polynomial time per tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Every finite connected graph has a spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] However, for infinite connected graphs, the existence of spanning trees is equivalent to the axiom of choice.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] An infinite graph is connected if each pair of its vertices forms the pair of endpoints of a finite path.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] As with finite graphs, a tree is a connected graph with no finite cycles, and a spanning tree can be defined either as a maximal acyclic set of edges or as a tree that contains every vertex.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] The trees within a graph may be partially ordered by their subgraph relation, and any infinite chain in this partial order has an upper bound (the union of the trees in the chain).
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Zorn's lemma, one of many equivalent statements to the axiom of choice, requires that a partial order in which all chains are upper bounded have a maximal element; in the partial order on the trees of the graph, this maximal element must be a spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Therefore, if Zorn's lemma is assumed, every infinite connected graph has a spanning tree.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] In the other direction, given a family of sets, it is possible to construct an infinite connected graph such that every spanning tree of the graph corresponds to a choice function of the family of sets.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Therefore, if every infinite connected graph has a spanning tree, then the axiom of choice is true.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] The idea of a spanning tree can be generalized to directed multigraphs.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] Given a vertex *v* on a directed multigraph *G*, an *oriented spanning tree* *T* rooted at *v* is an acyclic subgraph of *G* in which every vertex other than *v* has outdegree 1.
[src:prim-mst/spanning-tree] This definition is only satisfied when the "branches" of *T* point towards *v*.
